23:08.420 --> 23:10.570
And there's a problem
with his backstory.

23:10.590 --> 23:12.888
I just noticed it
this last time through.

23:12.890 --> 23:14.881
Uh, what-what sort of problem?

23:16.920 --> 23:19.127
The predatory nature
of his actions.

23:21.060 --> 23:23.620
You think he comes across
as predatory?

23:25.630 --> 23:28.895
I understand the impulse,
the Lolita myth.

23:28.900 --> 23:32.563
Not the Nabokov original
but the whole older man

23:32.570 --> 23:34.333
'inappropriately
young girl idea'

23:34.340 --> 23:37.070
that's been trashed
by lesser writers.

23:39.180 --> 23:42.069
Well, uh,
we can't all be Nabokov.

23:42.080 --> 23:44.947
Some of us can't even manage
Nicholas Sparks.

23:44.950 --> 23:46.611
Well, at least Sparks
understands what a reader

23:46.620 --> 23:49.680
can tolerate and what makes
their skin crawl.

23:50.960 --> 23:53.258
Are we looking
at the same pages here?

23:53.260 --> 23:56.320
Because they aren't
that far apart in age

23:56.330 --> 24:00.926
so I'm having a little trouble
seeing what you're seeing here.

24:00.940 --> 24:02.965
That's because he's your hero.

24:02.970 --> 24:05.598
_ _ Yo_u'_re invested
In justifying his actions.

24:05.610 --> 24:09.535
'You're too close _
to see him as he really is.'

24:09.540 --> 24:11.030
Listen, I'm just
being frank here.

24:11.050 --> 24:13.075
If-if I can't be frank,
I can't help you.

24:18.290 --> 24:20.781
- We all want the best book.
- Exactly.

24:20.790 --> 24:22.849
'And right now,
there's this friction'

24:22.860 --> 24:24.509
between your chapters
and Aria's.

24:24.530 --> 24:27.727
- Friction?
- Look.

24:27.730 --> 24:30.722
Neither one of us want
Aria to look foolish, right?

24:30.730 --> 24:32.823
Like she let herself
get talked into something

24:32.830 --> 24:34.969
that she didn't want.

24:34.970 --> 24:36.790
You mean Aria's character.

24:38.410 --> 24:40.059
Yeah, her character.

24:41.480 --> 24:43.732
I'm here to protect this book.

24:43.740 --> 24:47.073
And that means protecting
the authors. Both of them.

24:47.080 --> 24:48.809
Protecting from what?

24:48.820 --> 24:51.812
A loss of perspective.
Poor judgment.

24:51.820 --> 24:55.278
- Avoidable bad choices.
- That's a big responsibility.

24:56.660 --> 24:59.458
- And I take it very seriously.
- Yes.

25:01.160 --> 25:02.627
I can see that.

25:07.440 --> 25:09.169
I-I just, I understand
that I have commitments

25:09.170 --> 25:11.536
but I have commitments here too.

25:11.540 --> 25:14.259
'Yes, and you agreed.‘

25:14.280 --> 25:17.534
I will get a hard date
as soon as I can.

25:17.550 --> 25:19.347
Thank you. Bye.

25:19.350 --> 25:21.671
[sighs]

25:21.680 --> 25:24.717
- Hello, Spencer.
- Miss Drake.

25:24.720 --> 25:27.541
I saw you in here, and I thought
I'd ask about your friend.

25:27.560 --> 25:29.915
About Hanna. How is she?

25:29.920 --> 25:32.718
Uh, she's, she's alright.

25:32.730 --> 25:35.358
Has she told you any more
about what happened to her?

25:35.360 --> 25:37.225
No. No, not much.

25:37.230 --> 25:38.595
I have to tell you,
I don't feel

25:38.600 --> 25:40.022
especially good
about the other night.

25:40.030 --> 25:41.361
What about it?

25:41.370 --> 25:43.031
Letting Hanna talk me
into taking her

25:43.040 --> 25:45.861
to your house instead
of the police or the hospital.

25:45.870 --> 25:48.031
- So why did you?
- She insisted.

25:48.040 --> 25:51.635
Yes but you were the one
who was driving the car.

25:51.650 --> 25:52.969
You could have taken her
to the police.

25:52.980 --> 25:54.709
You could have taken her
to the doctor.

25:54.720 --> 25:58.042
You could have taken her
anywhere, but you didn't. Why?

25:58.050 --> 26:00.541
Frankly, Spencer,
my experiences with hospitals

26:00.560 --> 26:03.051
and the police haven't
always been the best.

26:03.060 --> 26:05.585
I'm sorry, what do you mean?

26:05.590 --> 26:09.890
I told you that my sister
and I had issues.

26:09.900 --> 26:12.892
That's true,
but not really honest.

26:12.900 --> 26:14.993
One of the most distressing
things about Alison

26:15.000 --> 26:16.558
being where she is
right now is that

26:16.570 --> 26:19.835
I have had similar experiences.

26:19.840 --> 26:23.401
I spent time,
considerable time

26:23.410 --> 26:25.469
in Radley when it was
a sanitarium.

26:27.180 --> 26:29.000
May I ask you why?

26:30.380 --> 26:33.087
Why you were at Radley?

26:35.860 --> 26:37.111
I'm gonna tell you this

26:37.120 --> 26:38.849
because I want you
to understand

26:38.860 --> 26:41.124
why I'm so worried
about Alison.

26:45.500 --> 26:48.196
We were 14, my sister and I.

26:48.200 --> 26:50.464
Jessica was babysitting.

26:50.470 --> 26:53.303
She called me to complain that
the baby wouldn't stop crying.

26:54.810 --> 26:57.802
It was the Carver baby, Teddy.

26:57.810 --> 27:00.472
He was ten months old,
and he had a cold

27:00.480 --> 27:02.277
and he must have been
miserable.

27:04.690 --> 27:06.487
She begged me
to come and help her.

27:06.490 --> 27:09.550
I didn't want to go,
but I did.

27:11.590 --> 27:14.423
And when I got there, the baby
was upstairs finally asleep.

27:14.430 --> 27:16.022
Jessica said
she had given him a bath

27:16.030 --> 27:17.292
and he had fallen right off.

27:18.830 --> 27:20.491
Then she asked me
to stay with Teddy

27:20.500 --> 27:24.197
so she could meet up
with Matt Brooks.

27:24.210 --> 27:26.007
Jessica left.

27:26.010 --> 27:29.901
And when the Carvers came home,
I told them that

27:29.910 --> 27:32.674
Jessica had called me
because she had a headache.

27:32.680 --> 27:34.272
Mrs. Carver went upstairs.

27:35.850 --> 27:39.411
Mr. Carver was giving me
Jessica's money.

27:41.860 --> 27:43.612
Mrs. Carver started to scream.

27:45.530 --> 27:47.452
_ She screamed
like she was on fire.

27:50.870 --> 27:52.497
Teddy was dead.

27:56.370 --> 27:57.860
When they found Jessica,
she said

27:57.870 --> 27:59.462
well, the baby had been fine
when she left.

28:01.040 --> 28:03.099
- But you told them--
- They believed Jessica.

28:04.480 --> 28:06.175
Everybody always
believed Jessica.

28:07.980 --> 28:09.447
She was the warm one.

28:10.820 --> 28:13.084
And that was why your parents
put you in Radley.

28:13.090 --> 28:14.614
It was that or prison.

28:17.260 --> 28:18.716
They thought I'd be safer.

28:21.100 --> 28:23.125
At least that's what
they told me.

28:27.270 --> 28:29.431
Are you sure?

28:29.440 --> 28:32.068
Liam can be really passionate
about writing.

28:32.070 --> 28:35.460
What I got wasn't criticism.
It was anger.

28:35.480 --> 28:37.436
Anger at what?

28:37.450 --> 28:40.248
At me.

28:40.250 --> 28:42.605
And I promised
to keep my side clean

28:42.620 --> 28:45.748
but if every note session
is gonna be a ten-round bout

28:45.750 --> 28:47.615
I-I don't know what's
gonna be left of this book

28:47.620 --> 28:49.451
or of any of us.

28:49.460 --> 28:52.088
I don't understand.

28:52.090 --> 28:57.050
Aria, what does Liam
really know about you and me?

29:01.870 --> 29:04.088
Well, this is the address.

29:04.110 --> 29:06.670
I'm afraid it's gone.

29:06.670 --> 29:08.467
No, it can't be gone.

29:08.480 --> 29:10.436
Oh, we haven't been here
in a long time.

29:10.440 --> 29:12.203
No, it cannot be gone.

29:12.210 --> 29:14.940
I mean, they-they can't just
take it away like that.

29:14.950 --> 29:16.269
You can't just pull out
a building

29:16.280 --> 29:17.474
like it was a bad tooth
or something.

29:17.490 --> 29:19.048
It's New York City, Hanna.

29:19.050 --> 29:20.449
They tear things down
as quickly as they put them up.

29:20.450 --> 29:22.111
Well, this was important.

29:22.120 --> 29:24.554
Okay, I needed this to be here
right where I left it.

29:24.560 --> 29:26.357
I was counting on it.

29:26.360 --> 29:28.351
I mean, Jordan,
this is where we first met.

29:28.360 --> 29:29.850
And now we don't have
a beginning anymore

29:29.860 --> 29:31.225
because they tore it down.

29:31.230 --> 29:32.788
Who do you people
think you are?

29:32.800 --> 29:35.667
Hey, hey, hey, hey.
What's wrong?

29:35.670 --> 29:37.092
Tell me and I'll fix it.

29:38.640 --> 29:40.369
I was gonna make it
perfect this time.

29:41.710 --> 29:44.508
You know, everybody gets
what they want.

29:44.510 --> 29:47.149
God, I had it all figured out
and now it's ruined.

29:47.150 --> 29:49.004
It's gone,
and it'll never work now.

29:49.020 --> 29:50.817
W—we'll just go someplace else.

29:50.820 --> 29:53.482
They'll just tear that down too.
Don't you get it?

29:53.490 --> 29:55.845
I'm a one-woman
demolition derby.

29:55.860 --> 29:57.487
Okay, I can't do this to you.

29:57.490 --> 29:58.889
What do you want?

30:00.390 --> 30:03.257
Hanna, I would move Heaven
and Earth for you?

30:04.600 --> 30:06.363
You know that, don't you?

30:06.370 --> 30:09.362
Yes...I do

30:09.370 --> 30:10.962
and I am so sorry.

30:14.210 --> 30:16.929
Hanna, come on.
This can't be it.

30:17.550 --> 30:20.303
[pop music]

30:32.130 --> 30:35.122
[instrumental music]

30:53.750 --> 30:55.149
(Emily)
'Miss Drake?‘

30:56.080 --> 30:57.911
Emily Fields.

30:57.920 --> 31:00.980
I was at Spencer's
when you dropped off Hanna.

31:00.990 --> 31:03.481
Emily. Yes.

31:03.490 --> 31:04.787
Are you staying here now?

31:04.790 --> 31:06.655
No, I was just..

31:07.800 --> 31:09.279
...thinking about
this place today

31:09.300 --> 31:12.428
and wondering
what it looked like now.

31:12.430 --> 31:14.523
Do you wanna sit down?

31:14.540 --> 31:16.394
Yes, I think I would.

31:25.810 --> 31:28.847
I saw they kept the big gates
out in front.

31:28.850 --> 31:32.172
Yeah, they did.

31:32.190 --> 31:35.887
At night, boys from town used
to rattle sticks on the bars.

31:35.890 --> 31:39.189
Somebody would dare them to go
to the nut house after midnight.

31:41.200 --> 31:44.499
I thought it was pretty
frightening during the day.

31:44.500 --> 31:46.968
It was.

31:46.970 --> 31:48.699
But sometimes
you find tenderness

31:48.700 --> 31:51.965
in the last place you'd expect.

31:51.970 --> 31:54.336
And that's really all
any of us needs to survive

31:54.340 --> 31:56.399
is a little tenderness
at the right moment.

31:59.850 --> 32:01.477
I went to visit Ali
this morning.

32:02.920 --> 32:04.512
How is she?

32:04.520 --> 32:05.976
They wouldn't let me in
to see her.

32:05.990 --> 32:07.412
Who wouldn't let you in?

32:07.420 --> 32:10.981
Elliot or Dr. Rollins.

32:10.990 --> 32:12.582
He doesn't want me
to see her either.

32:14.230 --> 32:16.255
But you-you've been talking
to him about her, right?

32:16.260 --> 32:18.524
Over the phone. Once.

32:18.530 --> 32:21.021
Are you satisfied with how
he's been taking care of her?

32:21.040 --> 32:22.564
Oh, yes.

32:23.200 --> 32:25.065
I suppose.

32:25.070 --> 32:27.607
Overall. I mean,
he's very professional.

32:28.340 --> 32:29.534
Yeah.

32:29.540 --> 32:31.428
But it_ does take some
getting used to him

32:31.450 --> 32:34.749
being her new husband
and her doctor.

32:37.020 --> 32:40.410
I'm the one
that took Ali to Welby

32:40.420 --> 32:43.912
and I can't help but wonder
ifI did the right thing.

32:44.730 --> 32:46.186
You wanted to help.

32:46.190 --> 32:48.454
Yeah, but I don't know ifI did.

32:50.030 --> 32:51.850
You're Ali's aunt.

32:51.870 --> 32:54.919
Maybe if you talk to somebody
at the sanitarium..

32:55.870 --> 32:57.132
I don't know, Emily.

32:57.140 --> 32:59.938
That would be
like challenging Dr. Rollins.

33:01.740 --> 33:04.868
Yeah, I understand.

33:04.880 --> 33:09.101
Perhaps you and I can go
to the sanitarium together.

33:11.290 --> 33:14.646
Look, I feel bad about
how we left things today.

33:14.660 --> 33:18.289
If we don't work on this project
together, it'll be another one.

33:18.290 --> 33:19.609
Can I borrow your pen?

33:19.630 --> 33:21.325
My pen?

33:21.330 --> 33:22.729
To sign these papers, partner.

33:24.300 --> 33:26.256
You're right. I want this.

33:26.270 --> 33:29.068
And right now, I want this
more than anything else.

33:42.280 --> 33:43.941
You said that
we could work together.

33:43.950 --> 33:45.542
That we could all be adults.

33:45.550 --> 33:47.780
- I meant it when I said it.
- Then what happened?

33:47.790 --> 33:49.212
I don't know.

33:49.220 --> 33:51.882
Reading his pages again
and then sitting there

33:51.890 --> 33:53.721
listening to him
while he was talking..

33:55.360 --> 33:57.521
He has a way with words.

33:57.530 --> 33:59.327
- I used to admire that.
- You don't anymore?

33:59.330 --> 34:01.059
No, now I am suspicious.

34:01.070 --> 34:02.321
Of what?

34:02.340 --> 34:05.036
It was a lot
of unconnected things

34:05.040 --> 34:07.634
that I didn't wanna connect
and then they clicked

34:07.640 --> 34:09.460
together on their own.

34:09.480 --> 34:11.471
Your history,
what you've been writing

34:11.480 --> 34:13.038
how you've been writing it.

34:13.050 --> 34:14.972
What changes in a room
when you guys are alone together

34:14.980 --> 34:16.470
and then somebody else walks in?

34:16.480 --> 34:20.541
Okay, and what do
all these connections mean?

34:23.160 --> 34:25.014
I think you were seduced
by your English teacher

34:25.030 --> 34:26.383
when you were in high school.

34:37.170 --> 34:38.432
It's not how it happened.

34:38.440 --> 34:39.691
I just gave you a great opening
to lie one more time

34:39.710 --> 34:41.405
and you didn't take it.

34:43.440 --> 34:47.274
Look, there is no way that I can
possibly explain this to you.

34:47.280 --> 34:50.169
Then try by telling me how
you'd explain it to yourself.

34:54.350 --> 34:57.114
Okay, I used to think
what if there was a button

34:57.120 --> 35:00.624
that I could push
and all of the things

35:00.630 --> 35:04.122
that have complicated my life
would just unhappen?

35:04.130 --> 35:05.893
I would push it,
and all of the people

35:05.900 --> 35:07.458
that shouldn't have died
would still be alive.

35:07.470 --> 35:09.961
I wouldn't have hurt anyone
or disappointed them

35:09.970 --> 35:11.858
and no one would have
hurt me or lied to me

35:11.870 --> 35:14.566
and this whole mess
would just be cleaned up.

35:14.580 --> 35:17.333
But if I push that button,
I would be gone too.

35:19.280 --> 35:21.145
I am me
because of what has happened

35:21.150 --> 35:23.175
what I've done
and because of who I love.

35:26.390 --> 35:29.541
I like that person.

35:29.560 --> 35:31.949
'That me.‘

35:31.960 --> 35:33.382
Mess and all.

35:45.840 --> 35:47.933
(Alison)
Emily?'

35:47.940 --> 35:50.738
You were supposed
to wake me up.

35:50.740 --> 35:52.799
It took me longer to get here
than I thought it would.

35:54.780 --> 35:56.839
I can't move.

35:56.850 --> 36:00.013
I think
something's wrong with me.

36:00.020 --> 36:01.339
You're in the hospital.

36:03.020 --> 36:05.409
We're gonna miss our flight.

36:05.430 --> 36:06.749
We'll take the next one.

36:10.660 --> 36:13.094
Ali, you called me last night.

36:13.100 --> 36:14.522
Did I?

36:14.540 --> 36:16.098
Yeah.

36:16.100 --> 36:18.364
And you sounded scared.

36:18.370 --> 36:20.600
Like you wanted help.

36:20.610 --> 36:22.407
This is a scary place.

36:25.110 --> 36:27.169
There's this lady
that cries all night.

36:31.120 --> 36:33.042
Am I in Radley?

36:33.050 --> 36:35.189
No. No.

36:37.220 --> 36:39.359
Well, that's good.

36:39.360 --> 36:40.782
I was worried for a minute.

36:40.790 --> 36:42.189
[sighs]

36:47.030 --> 36:49.123
Mommy?

36:49.140 --> 36:51.461
'Why did you leave me?‘

36:51.470 --> 36:54.303
I woke up,
and there was dirt all over me

36:54.310 --> 36:57.131
and you wouldn't help.

36:57.140 --> 36:59.802
[crying]
Why did you leave me
in the ground?

36:59.810 --> 37:01.243
It's so cold.

37:01.250 --> 37:02.478
Alison.

37:02.480 --> 37:04.846
You were wrong about Elliot.

